Assignment 1

In this you assignment will explore the sleep times of different mammals. The dataset is called msleep and comes with the ggplot2 package (which in turn comes with tidyverse). After loading the tidyverse package, you can use the command data(msleep) to load the dataset into the environment in R. Use ?msleep in R if you want to get some information about the dataset. Your assignment tasks are the provided below along with a skeleton code (ListingÂ 1) for you to base your code on. Save this as your own .R script and submit it through canvas after testing it in the auto-corrector. Make sure your code adheres to the following guidelines:

  • All visualizations are made with ggplot.
  • Your code does not overwrite or modify any of the variables in the skeleton code after completing each task. It will cause the auto-corrector to fail.
  • Your code passes the auto-corrector test in the auto-corrector. If you do not manage to solve this before the deadline, submit any way.

Good luck!

  1. Copy the skeleton code (ListingÂ 1) at the bottom of the page to you own .R file.
  2. The variables genus, vore, order and conservation are of character type. Convert them into factors and make sure the resulting data frame is still called msleep.
  3. Which animal has the shortest sleep time? Store the sleep time of this animal in a numeric variable called shortest_sleep and the name of the animal in a character/string variable called shortest_sleep_mammal.
  4. There are some variables with missing values. Which variable has the most values missing? Store the name of the variable in a character/string variable called most_missing and the number of missing values (for that same variable) in a numeric variable called missing_values.
  5. Compute the correlations between all numeric variables in the dataset. Save the result in a variable called correlations.
    • Hint: To compute correlations in spite of missing values, set the use argument to "pairwise.complete.obs" or "complete.obs" in the correlation function.
  6. Of course, there is a strong negative correlation between sleep_total and awake as more time awake automatically leads to less time asleep. If we disregard the correlation between these two variables, which variables are most strongly correlated? Copy the correlation matrix from Task 4 to a new variable, find the second most correlated variables, and save the correlation in a numeric variable called highest_corr.
    • Hint: If you want more of a challenge, see the hint on Canvas on selecting elements in a matrix and try to solve the task programmatically. Otherwise it is okay to just visually inspect the correlation matrix and store the number as a variable.
  7. How are the sleep times distributed? Create a histogram for the sleep_total variable. Save the histogram in a variable called sleep_histogram. Remember to use ggplot.
  8. Different mammals eat different things. We have data on which animals are herbivores, carnivores, omnivores, insectivores (some mammals are also missing this type of data). Create a bar chart with each bar containing the number of mammals in each food category. Store the plot in a variable called food_barchart.
  9. Which type of mammal in our data sleeps the most? Create a boxplot for the sleep_total variable, grouped so that there is one box for each food category. Make sure the total sleep time is on the y axis and store the resulting plot in a variable called sleep_boxplot.
  10. For which food category do the mammals have the longest average sleep time? Store the average time for this group in a variable called highest_average.
  11. Do mammals who sleep more also have more rem sleep? Create a scatterplot plotting total sleep time against rem sleep time with rem sleep on the y axis. Note that we we also have different orders of animals. These have latin names such as Rodentia, Artiodactyla, etcâ¦ color the points by the order of each animal and store the resulting plot in a variable called sleep_scatterplot.
  12. Using only data for the most common order (most prevalent in the data), create another scatterplot plotting their total sleep time against their rem sleep. Again, put rem sleep on the y axis and save the resulting plot in a variable called sleep_scatterplot2.
  13. Make sure your R script runs from top to bottom after clearing the environment and restarting R/RStudio.
